  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some lesser-known sights to see when visiting Aurora, IL?",
  "response": "Aurora, IL, known as the \"City of Lights,\" has plenty to offer beyond its well-known attractions like the Paramount Theatre and the RiverEdge Park. Here are some lesser-known sights that are worth exploring when you visit:\n\n1. **Phillips Park Zoo**\n   Located within Phillips Park, this small but charming zoo is home to a variety of animals, including bison, bears, and a range of birds. It's a great place for a family outing, and admission is free, although donations are appreciated.\n\n2. **Aurora Regional Fire Museum**\n   Housed in the old Central Fire Station, this museum offers a fascinating look at the history of firefighting in Aurora. You can see vintage fire trucks, equipment, and even a small exhibit on fire safety.\n\n3. **The GAR Memorial Hall**\n   This historic building was originally built as a meeting place for the Grand Army of the Republic, a fraternal organization of Union Civil War veterans. Today, it's a museum showcasing Civil War artifacts and memorabilia.\n\n4. **Aurora Historical Society Museum**\n   Located in a restored 1857 church, this museum offers an in-depth look at the history of Aurora. The exhibits cover everything from the city's early days to its role in the development of the region.\n\n5. **Blackberry Farm**\n   This living history museum features a working farm from the 1840s. Visitors can ride a steam train, visit a pioneer village, and see demonstrations of traditional crafts like blacksmithing and woodworking.\n\n6. **Aurora Public Art Trail**\n   While not a single site, the Public Art Trail is a great way to explore the city's artistic side. The trail features over 200 pieces of public art, including murals, sculptures, and installations, scattered throughout the city.\n\n7. **The David L. Pierce Art and History Center**\n   Located in a beautiful historic building, this center features rotating exhibits that showcase the work of local artists and historians. It's a great place to learn more about the cultural heritage of Aurora.\n\n8. **Tanner House Museum**\n   This beautifully restored Victorian mansion offers a glimpse into the life of a prosperous family in the late 19th century. The house is filled with period furnishings and artifacts, and guided tours are available.\n\nThese lesser-known attractions offer a more intimate look at the history, culture, and natural beauty of Aurora, IL. Whether you're a history buff, an art lover, or just looking for something off the beaten path, these sites are definitely worth a visit.",
